g to keep all the factions together was a bit of a hastle, but nothing that doesn't sink in over time. It's relatively easy to find where your in-game loyalties lie. This game is SUPER sidequest heavy. It was tedious. Going back and forth a lot. There's also a resting mechanic, where you 'have' to rest every in-game 24 hours or so. You really don't, it doesn't impact gameplay or combat (it might in the higher difficulties, idk) but resting otherwise just grants you bonus xp from battles. Leveling up is also very easy. I ended the game at around level 38 or so, which lets you do a lot if you invest in a single skill set and combo style from the start. Character customization is relativley limited, but is limited with really good looking options. It's pretty much guaranteed you'll be satisfied with how your character looks. Also, the games currency can be acquired through extraction of living things. You can get it from animals and farming them for it. Which is also a good way to rack up xp. You can also get it from humans too. However, this is more of a renegade rout, and kills them which has an impact on the way your companions view them. I avoided it for the most part, except when there were moments where it came down to letting a person go, or having them killed. Depends on your morals. Anyway, I didn't go around extracting people, and I didn't run into many problems as far as currency was related in the game. So it's better just not to do it.\n      Now finally, my last reason I have to say why I loved this game was because of the characters and romance option. I mean, duh, it's an rpg, of course the romance has to be good. They are all really great. I personally think that the voice acting was great, and you can tell this is a game where a lot of thought and work was put into it. Occasionally if you find that you built up your charisma to be high early on, you'll find that people will cave in to suggestions pretty easily most of the time. This sometimes takes away from the challenge of opposing viewpoints, but it gets you through the game at least. Back to the romance, I want to state right off the back that this is a great game for people in the LGBT community. The other deciding factor besides the sale, and the only real reason that made my decision to give this game a try was because of how the m/m romace was portrayed. The main character is canonically bisexual, and both romance options have been given a lot of thought, personality, and depth. Of course, the romance is secondary to the game, and the interactions for that branch are limited. But this game's got great representation. By that, I mean the romance is natural, sweet, and doesn't end in soul crushing death or disapointment for the sake of giving the game an edge. Genuine representation. And you get an achievement for it too. And it's called Soulmate, how f***ing cute is that? So yeah, my 2 cents on it. It was rediculous when it was, what, 70 bucks when it first came out? I wouldn't pay that much for it, but then again, I wouldn't pay that much for any game really. If it was 20 bucks, and I bought it, I would have considered it a worthy purchase. I think it is a great game. If you have doubts, wait until it's 75% off and get it. Just abandon any connections between other rpgs you've played, and immerse yourself in the uniqueness of this one, and I think you shouldn't have too many reasons not to enjoy it.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505031824, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505032650, "recommendationid": "34856280", "language": "english", "votes_down": 1, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.508515", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505013801, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 9, "playtime_forever": 253, "steamid": "76561198059857882", "num_games_owned": 301}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 14, "comment_count": 0, "review": "I tried. I sinceraly and honestly tried to like