 of corporations controlling their city and immediate area beyond (mostly where the sun don't shine, quite literally) and competing with other corporations through polticial pressure or outright war. Compare it to Fallout, Mad Max, or even Warhammer 40k, you'll find comparisons, not in the least of the ASC, the scary, secret police that plays an integral role in the game and in design would remind anyone familiar with it of WH40k's Inquisition.\n\nOur protagonist, Zachariah Rogue Mancer, born and bred in the corporation/city of Abundance, finds himself tossed in the middle of this world. Life in Abundance is harsh, hierarchical and based on a clear caste-system, which reflects in the initally \"silly\" last name that the protagonist and other Technomancers carry: he is called Mancer because he is a Technomancer and deemed to belong to that \"Family\". Similarly, he carries the name of Rogue (although Mancer, being of a higher family in the hierarchy, supersedes his previous name of Rogue) to reflect his origins in the slums dominated by \"criminal\" activity. NPCs carry similar names according to their role in society and it is flat out stated that jobs have become hereditary. We are left with a archetypical but well-designed post-apocalyptic feel, where advanced technology is prevalent but existence is ruled by pragmatism and to some extent, harsh Darwinism.\n\nIt is worth comparing this game to the likes of The Witcher or Mass Effect, as they are RPGs similar in nature though very different in setting. In all cases you play a protagonist character that has a name and some predefined history, but make further choices during the story's development as to the exact nature of your persona and his role in the environment. Make no mistake, you are Zachariah Mancer, trained Technomancer, officer in the army. You do not have the freedom to define yourself completely, and some game mechanics, specifically the reputation and karma systems, will react because of this. At the very start of the game, you are clearly told by your instructor that human life is precious and that you should disable opponents without killing them (even though you have the option and it even pays you to kill). I was never bothered by this \"lack of freedom\". I don't need to be a nameless hero. I'm fine playing Zach Mancer in this story, even if that means that the game slaps me with a Karma penalty every time I kill somebody. It's like playing a Renegade Shepard, or a Geralt that demands payment from the poor populance for every monster slain. It is my job.\n\nThe first thing I felt the game dropped the ball a little was in combat gameplay. Combat design is interesting, diverse, and mostly fluid, and it is obvious to see what the developers worked towards. However it also feels a little unpolished and needlessly complicated. As a Technomancer, you have your Technomancer powers at your disposal as well as 3 different combat styles, one which (\"Staff\" or \"Warrior\" style) is clearly linked to Technomancy. The downside is that it seems like the other two styles of Rogue and Guardian (tank) were kinda tacked on for the sake of diversity, though it is worth noting they are viable for gameplay. I went with the obvious choice: fighting with a staff and using my Technomancer powers to buff my staff combat and throwing lightning bolts when desired. \n\nI have to admit I've never felt more like a Jedi Knight, not even in any actual Star Wars game I ever played. Warrior Zach dances around the battlefield like he's one with the Force, dodging both melee blows and gunshots with equal ease. The only criticism I can give about combat it doesn't always feel like I am in control. Granted, I started out on Hard difficulty and I did not expect to not die, but frequently I find I die because the game doesn't seem to really do what I want. Dodging too quickly in succession sends me twice in the same direction even though I pressed the buttons to dodge in another direction. Opponents frequently interrupt me in combat, mostly based on random battle outcomes due to previous actions. In a way such things make sense, I should not expect (due to physics) that I can dodge in a different direction at a 90 degree angle after jumping this way... but then I am also dodging bullets here. My suspension of disblief doesn't really want to suspend its own suspension.\n\nAdd to this that, despite the many buttons to press that are available, combat is a bit repetitive, in that a staff attack will mostly just repeat the same staff strike over and over, and it feels like combat is just a little unpolished. Like it worked pretty well, and they just decided that 80% of the overall idea was good enough. It is just difficult enough to not let me get away with sheer button-bashing (though the semi-randomness of combat lets me do that frequently enough, even on Hard), but not so difficult that I can't bumble through hard difficulty on a first playthrough with some experimentation and a few retries on bossfights.\n\nStorywise, the game seems... a bit iffy to me so far. It feels like there's a lot it's not telling me, but it kinda expects me to make choices based on it anyway. In a game that makes it clear quickly that I am playing Zach Mancer and that killing is bad, it also seems very eager to throw some moral dilemmas at me. The first mission pretty much pits the morality I was taught in the introduction against the needs of the military that protects society, as some quest targets don't complete unless you *choose* to kill. The game does not halt your progress for it, but your questgiver will whine at you for it, and such a situation occurred more frequently. Whilst a completionist/perfectionist like me might balk at this I would nonetheless consider this a good thing: the game does its best to emphasise your choices have consequences, even if the consequence is just a little whiny line in the dialogue. \n\nSimultaneously, I felt a little deprived of information. The game quickly bombarded me with factions, without actually telling me these are factions, and there are factions in Abundance (pun intended). Some dilemmas jumped the gun a bit, gameplaywise. Storywise I can fully understand that these factions have been around, that the issues of society are long-term... but I am the player. I just got here. And I'm supposed to be Zach... so how the hell am I supposed to know if it's a good idea to let the sympathetic rebel leader go or push the arrest? Whilst I'd love to make my own decision about whether Zach is Officer Hardass or Lieutenant Sympathetic, I feel a little miffed when as a consequence the game slaps me with Karma stat penalties for my choice. Technomancer doesn't seem to have figured out whether it wanted to go for the freedom of decision, or a story-driven character development, and with the current hyrbid-ish solution it just feels like it fails at both.\n\nIn conclusion, The Technomancer is an enjoyable game, but feels a bit unpolished. From the somewhat clunky combat, to some a few quest glitches, down to the spelling errors in the subtitles, it seems like it could've used some more attention before release. What I expected was an RPG where I could play a sci-fi lightning-throwing-fighting protagonist... and what I got was everything I expected, so I heartily recommend giving The Technomancher a chance.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1506117091, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1506117091, "recommendationid": "35138497", "language": "english", "votes_down": 3, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.497042", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505688313, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 1540, "steamid": "76561198083640040", "num_games_owned": 126}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 2, "comment_count": 0, "review": "dont buy this buggy piece of crap. i had 2 quests going for one of the companions \"Amellia\". 